            }
          ],
          "DETECTOR": [
            {
              "pointer": "",
              "coded_information": [
                "TELES",
                "SIBAR",
                "SI"
              ],
              "free_text": [
                " Three dE-E telescopes were used in",
                "the experiment. The 20-50mu-m(dE) and 2mm(E) silicon",
                "detectors in two telescopes to detect heavy reaction",
                "products.A third telescope with 500 mu-m silicon(dE)",
                "and 7cm NaJ(Tl) detectors was used for detection of",
                "light reaction products."
              ]
            }
          ],
          "ERR-ANALYS": [
            {
              "pointer": "",
              "coded_information": {
                "heading": "EN-ERR",
                "minimum_value": null,
                "maximum_value": null,
                "correlation_property": null
              },
              "free_text": [
                " The error in the estimation of the",
                " energy spread of the beam"
              ]
            },
            {
              "pointer": "",
              "coded_information": {
                "heading": "ERR-T",
                "minimum_value": null,
                "maximum_value": null,
                "correlation_property": null
              },
              "free_text": [
                " Uncertainties are included normalization error",
                "and statistical errors (around 15%).",
                "The angular distributions were obtained by normalizing",
                "on a factor found for the elastic scattering by",
                "two methods:",
                " (1) using information about target thickness, solid",
                "     angles of detectors and the charge  collected in",
                "     the measurement;",
                " (2) normalizing the relative elastic cross sections",
                "     to the optical model predictions at  forward",
                "     angles using a few global optical potentials"
              ]
            }
          ],
